ee variables: can take any value in {0, ..., p-1}\n\n5. **Find optimal solution:**\n   - Express pivot vars as functions of free vars\n   - Enumerate free variable assignments to find minimum total presses\n   - Tiebreak with lexicographic ordering\n\n### Optimization Strategy for Solution Search\n\nGiven k free variables over GF(p):\n\n- **Small search space** (p^k ≤ ~2M): Direct enumeration of all free variable assignments. Compute full solution for each, track best.\n- **Larger search space in GF(2)**: Meet-in-the-middle — split free vars into two halves, enumerate each half's contribution, use a map to find optimal combinations.\n- **Larger search space in GF(p>2)**: Meet-in-the-middle generalized to GF(p).\n\nFor each candidate solution, \"cost\" = sum of all variable values (in {0,...,p-1}). Among equal costs, prefer lex-smallest.\n\n### Modular Arithmetic Utilities\n\n- `mod(a, p)`: Always-positive modulo\n- `modInverse(a, p)`: Multiplicative inverse via extended Euclidean algorithm\n- `modAdd(a, b, p)`, `modMul(a, b, p)`: Basic operations\n\n### API Wrappers\n\n**`solveToggle(machine: Machine): number[] | null`**\n- Builds matrix from `machine.buttons` and `machine.target`\n- Calls core solver with modulus=2\n- Converts solution to sorted list of button indices where value=1\n- Returns null if no solution\n\n**`solveCounter(lights, buttons, modulus): number[] | null`**\n- Builds matrix from buttons and lights\n- Calls core solver with given modulus\n- Returns the press-count array directly\n- Returns null if no solution\n\n## Data Flow\n\n```\nInput → Build augmented matrix → Gaussian elimination (RREF)\n  → Check consistency → Identify free/pivot vars\n  → Enumerate/MITM over free vars → Pick optimal → Format output\n```\n\n## Key Decisions\n\n1. **Unified solver**: One GF(p) implementation handles both puzzles\n2. **Plain number arrays**: No bitwise tricks needed for 40×40 matrices\n3. **MITM for large null spaces**: Handles up to ~40 free variables efficiently\n4. **Greedy lex ordering**: During enumeration, process in order to get lex-smallest naturally\n\n## Testing Plan\n\n- Spec example (no solution case)\n- Simple solvable cases (single button, identity mapping)\n- Multiple solutions → verify minimum presses and lex ordering\n- Edge cases: 0 lights, 0 buttons, all-false target, all-true target\n- Large systems (40×40) for performance\n- Counter puzzle with various prime moduli (2, 3, 5, 7, 97)\n- Counter puzzle with free variables and non-trivial optimal solutions\n\n## File Structure\n\n```\nsrc/\n  index.ts          — exports solveToggle, solveCounter, Machine interface\n  solver.ts         — core GF(p) linear system solver\n  modular.ts        — modular arithmetic utilities\n```\n","numLines":99,"startLine":1,"totalLines":99}}}
